  "prompt": "Is divorce in India one-sided?",
  "response": "Divorce in India can be complex and varies depending on personal laws of different religious communities. Here are some key points:\n\n1. Different laws for different communities:\n- Hindus follow Hindu Marriage Act\n- Muslims have their own personal laws\n- Christians have separate provisions\n- Special Marriage Act for inter-religious marriages\n\n2. Grounds for divorce:\n- Mutual consent divorce is generally easier\n- One-sided divorce is possible under certain conditions like:\n  \u2022 Adultery\n  \u2022 Cruelty\n  \u2022 Desertion\n  \u2022 Conversion\n  \u2022 Mental disorder\n  \u2022 Communicable disease\n\n3. Gender perspectives:\n- Traditionally, divorce proceedings were considered more challenging for women\n- Recent legal reforms have aimed to provide more balanced rights\n- Women now have more legal protections and grounds for divorce\n\n4. Recent developments:\n- Supreme Court has made divorce procedures more equitable\n- Courts encourage mutual consent and mediation\n- Legal processes have become relatively more gender-neutral\n\n5. Challenges:\n- Social stigma still exists\n- Legal procedures can be lengthy and expensive\n- Implementation varies across different states and communities\n\nWhile not entirely one-sided, the divorce process in India remains complex and context-dependent.",
